14/http://www.du.edu/~jcalvert/tel/morse/morse.htm History of electromagnetic telegraph]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080919171140/http://www.connected-earth.co.uk/Galleries/Telecommunicationsage/Thetelegraph/Thefirstelectrictelegraphs/index.htm The first electric telegraphs]\n* [http://www.computer-museum.ru/connect/chlitlgr.htm The Dawn of Telegraphy] {{in lang|ru}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110927132314/http://www.pcweek.ru/Year2002/N3/CP1251/Communications/chapt3.htm Pavel Shilling and his telegraph]- article in ''PCWeek'', Russian edition.\n* [http://distantwriting.co.uk/ Distant Writing] - The History of the Telegraph Companies in Britain between 1838 and 1868\n* [https://science.nasa.gov/headlines/y2008/06may_carringtonflare.htm? NASA - Carrington Super Flare] [[NASA]] 6 May 2008\n* [https://books.google.com/books?id=DI038d4SBFEC&printsec=titlepage#PPA2298,M1 How Cables Unite The World] - a 1902 article about telegraph networks and technology from the magazine ''[[The World's Work]]''\n* {{Cite NIE|wstitle=Telegraph|short=x}}\n\n{{Morse code}}\n{{Telecommunications}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Telegraphy]]\n[[Category:Russian inventions]]\n[[Category:19th-century inventions]]\n\n[[sl:Telegraf]]\n[[fi:Lenn\u00e4tin]]\n[[zh:\u7535\u62a5]]\n", "name_user": "Egerity", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed \"impregnated\" to \"infused\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_telegraph"}
{"title_page": "DuSable Bridge", "text_new": "{{Infobox bridge\n|bridge_name   = DuSable Bridge\n|image         = Michigan Ave Bridge 20100912.jpg\n|caption       = DuSable (Michigan Avenue) Bridge viewed from the west\n|official_name = \n|carries       = [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]]\n|crosses       = [[Chicago River]]\n|locale        = [[Chicago]]\n|maint         = \n|id            = 000016612026812\n|designer      = Bureau of Engineering, [[Chicago Department of Public Works]]\n|design        = Double-leaf, double-deck, fixed [[counterweight]], [[trunnion]] [[bascule bridge]]\n|material      =\n|spans         =\n|pierswater    = \n|length= {{convert|399|ft|m}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Holth|first=Nathan|title=Michigan Avenue Bridge|url=http://www.historicbridges.org/truss/michiganavenue/|work=HistoricBridges.org|accessdate=September 19, 2010}}</ref>\n|width= {{convert|91.75|ft|m}}<ref name=\"HAER\">{{cite web|last=Scott|first=Charles|last2=Alexander|first2=Frances|last3=Nicolay|first3=John|last4=Brucken|first4=Carolyn|title=Chicago River Bascule Bridge, Michigan Avenue|url=http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.pnp/hhh.il0630|work=Historic American Engineering Record|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=September 19, 2010}}</ref>\n|mainspan= {{convert|256|ft|m}} between trunnions<br />{{convert|220|ft|m}} between piers<ref name=\"Young 1920 p508\">{{Harvnb|Young|1920|p=508}}</ref>\n|height        = \n|load          = \n|clearance     = \n|below         = {{convert|16|ft|m}}\n|traffic       = 37900 (upper deck)<br />11700 (lower deck)<ref>2010 data from the National Bridge Inventory Database. {{cite web|title=National Bridge Inventory|url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/bridge/nbi/ascii.cfm?year=2011|publisher=U.S. Department of Transportation Federal Highway Administration|accessdate=2012-04-04}}</ref>\n|begin = April 15, 1918<ref name=\"Tribune19200514\">{{cite news|title=\"I Will\" Spirit Wins; Open Link Bridge Today|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=May 14, 1920|page=3}}</ref>\n|complete = 1920\n|open=May 14, 1920<ref name=\"Tribune19200514\" />\n|heritage = [[List of Chicago Landmarks|Chicago Landmark]]\n|collapsed     =\n|preceded      =\n|followed      =\n|closed        = \n|toll          = \n|map_cue       = \n|map_image     = \n|map_text      = \n|map_width     = \n|coordinates   = {{coord|41|53|19.9|N|87|37|27.7|W|region:US_type:landmark|display=it}}\n|extra         =\n}}\nThe '''DuSable Bridge''' (formerly, '''Michigan Avenue Bridge''') is a [[bascule bridge]] that carries [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]] across the main stem of the [[Chicago River]] in downtown [[Chicago]], Illinois, United States. The bridge was proposed in the early 20th century as part of a plan to link Chicago's south side and north side parks with a grand boulevard. Construction of the bridge started in 1918, it opened to traffic in 1920, and decorative work was completed in 1928. The bridge provides passage for vehicles and pedestrians on two levels. An example of a fixed [[trunnion]] bascule bridge (which is also known as a \"Chicago style bascule bridge\"), it may be raised to allow tall ships and boats to pass underneath. The bridge is included in the [[Michigan\u2013Wacker Historic District]] and has been designated as a [[Chicago Landmark]].\n\nThe location is significant in the early history of Chicago, connecting on the north near the 1780s homestead site of [[Jean Baptiste Point du Sable]] and on the south the early 19th century site of [[Fort Dearborn]]. Events from the city's past are commemorated with sculptures and plaques on the bridge, and exhibits in the McCormick Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum\u2014housed in one of the [[bridge tender's house|bridge tender houses]]\u2014detail the history of the Chicago River.\n\n==Location==\n{{multiple image\n| align=left\n| footer   = Aerial view of the bridge, looking south along [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]], 1945 (left) and 2008 (right) \n| width    = 127\n\n| image1   = Michigan Ave looking south, Chicago, 6-20-1945.jpg\n| alt1     = 1945\n\n| image2   = Michigan Avenue Bridge 20080811.jpg\n| alt2     = 2010\n}}\n\nThe Michigan Avenue Bridge has a north\u2013south orientation, spanning the main stem of the Chicago River between the [[Near North Side, Chicago|Near North Side]] and [[Loop, Chicago|Loop]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community areas]] of Chicago.<ref>{{cite map |publisher=Google Inc |title=Google Maps |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?q=41.888861,-87.624361(Michigan+Avenue+Bridge)&ie=UTF8&ll=41.88886,-87.624357&spn=0.003582,0.005901&z=18 |accessdate=October 10, 2010}}</ref> Its northern portal lies at the foot of the [[Magnificent Mile]], between the [[Wrigley Building]] and [[Tribune Tower]]. Its southern portal is at the intersection of Michigan Avenue and [[Wacker Drive]], overlooked by the [[London Guarantee Building]] and [[333 North Michigan]]. The neighboring bridges are [[Columbus Drive Bridge (Chicago)|Columbus Drive Bridge]] to the east and [[Wabash Avenue Bridge]] to the west.\n\nThe bridge is situated in a historically significant area.<ref>{{cite book|last=Stamper|first=John W.|title=North Michigan Avenue: a building book from the Chicago Historical Society|year=2005|publisher=Pomegranate|isbn=0-7649-3382-5|page=8}}</ref> The northern end of the bridge covers part of the [[Jean Baptiste Point Du Sable Homesite]],{{#tag:ref|According to an 1892 description of the location of the house, it \"stood as nearly as may be at the foot of Pine Street <nowiki>[</nowiki>now Michigan Avenue<nowiki>]</nowiki>, partly upon the ground now occupied by Kirk's factory, and partly in what is now known as North Water Street, properly an extension of Kinzie Street.\" This location was confirmed by the recollections of John Noble, the last occupant of the house, who died in 1888.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mason|first=Edward G.|title=Early Visitors to Chicago|journal=The New England Magazine|date=April 1892|volume=6|issue=2|pages=188\u2013206}}</ref>|group=n}} which is commemorated by a National Historic plaque in [[Pioneer Court]]. The southern half of the bridge passes over the site of [[Fort Dearborn]], which was constructed in 1803.{{#tag:ref|The south bank of the river where Fort Dearborn had stood was dredged in 1855, straightening the bend in the river and widening it at this point by about {{convert|150|ft|m}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Andreas|first=Alfred T.|title=History of Chicago, Volume 1|year=1884|publisher=A. T. Andreas|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofchicago01inandr|accessdate=September 19, 2010|page=[https://archive.org/details/historyofchicago01inandr/page/238 238]}}</ref>|group=n}} The Fort is commemorated by a large [[relief]] above the entrance of the London Guarantee Building, and brass markers positioned in the sidewalks on the south side of the bridge delineate the posited outline of the original [[blockhouse]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Old Fort Dearborn Site to be Outlined on Michigan Avenue|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=January 8, 1941}}</ref>\n\n==Name==\nThe historical significance of the location has been used as the basis for a number of proposals to rename the bridge. In 1921 the Chicago Historical Society suggested that the bridge should be named ''[[Jacques Marquette|Marquette]]\u2013[[Louis Joliet|Joliet]] Bridge'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Ave Bridge it is, and so it Stays|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=April 7, 1921}}</ref> and in 1939 it was proposed to rename the bridge as ''Fort Dearborn Bridge''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Urge Renaming of Bridge in Honor of Ft. Dearborn|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=October 29, 1939}}</ref> These proposals were not adopted.\n\nIn October 2010, the bridge was renamed ''DuSable Bridge'' in honor of [[Jean Baptiste Point du Sable]], Chicago's first permanent resident.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cancino |first=Alejandra |title=Michigan Avenue bridge officially renamed DuSable Bridge |url=http://www.chicagobreakingnews.com/2010/10/michigan-avenue-bridge-officially-renamed-dusable-bridge.html |accessdate=October 16, 2010 |newspaper=Chicago Breaking News |date=October 15, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101019044214/http://www.chicagobreakingnews.com/2010/10/michigan-avenue-bridge-officially-renamed-dusable-bridge.html |archivedate=October 19, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A fur trader of African descent who married into the [[Potawatomi]] tribe, he established a permanent homestead and trading post near the mouth of the Chicago River in the 1780s.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Avenue Bridge becomes DuSable Bridge|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wls/story?section=news/local&id=7726430|accessdate=October 17, 2010|newspaper=WLS-TV|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101018072553/http://abclocal.go.com/wls/story?section=news%2Flocal&id=7726430|archive-date=October 18, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Plan of Chicago Plate CXII.jpg|thumb|right|Michigan Boulevard and bridge as proposed in Burnham & Bennett's [[1909 Plan of Chicago]] looking north from [[Grant Park (Chicago)|Grant Park]]]]\nA boulevard to link the parks on Chicago's north and south sides was proposed as early as 1891.<ref name=\"Tribune19200514\" /> An early plan called for a tunnel to link Michigan Avenue south of the river with Pine Street (now Michigan Avenue) north of the river.<ref>{{cite news|title=Great Boulevard Subway Project for Connecting North and South Divisions of the City|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=January 22, 1903|page=3}}</ref> In 1903 an editorial in the Chicago Tribune proposed a new bascule bridge across the river at Michigan Avenue.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Michigan Avenue Dream|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=May 31, 1903|page=16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Experts Praise Boulevard Plan|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=June 21, 1903|page=8}}</ref> Other plans suggested that the bridge should be a replica of the [[Pont Alexandre III]] that spans the Seine in Paris, or that, rather than constructing an entirely new bridge, the existing Rush Street bridge should be double-decked.<ref>{{cite news|title=Many Plans are Submitted for the Boulevard Link|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=June 11, 1904|page=4}}</ref>\n\nPlans for the boulevard and the construction of a Michigan Avenue Bridge were further elaborated upon in [[Daniel Burnham]]'s [[1909 Plan of Chicago]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Burnham|Bennett|1909|pp=101\u2013107}}</ref> In 1911 a plan was selected that included the widening of Michigan Avenue from Randolph Street to the river, replacing the Rush Street bridge with a new bridge at Michigan Avenue and the construction of a double-decked boulevard along Pine Street as far as Ohio Street.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wide Boulevard Scheme Chosen|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=July 11, 1911|page=3}}</ref> An ordinance to fund construction was passed in 1913, but was declared void by the [[Supreme Court of Illinois]].<ref>{{cite news|title=No Beginning on Boulevard Link for Three Years|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=May 6, 1915|page=13}}</ref> A second ordinance was passed in 1914, but legal battles continued until the end of 1916.<ref>{{cite news|title=Last Obstacle to Boulevard Link Removed|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=December 29, 1916|page=2}}</ref> Construction finally started on April 15, 1918, and the bridge was officially opened in a ceremony on May 14, 1920.<ref name=\"Tribune19200514\" />\n\nThe bridge is one of the contributing properties of the [[Michigan\u2013Wacker Historic District]], which was listed as on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on November 15, 1978.<ref name=\"nrhpdoc\">{{Cite journal|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Michigan\u2013Wacker Historic District |url=http://gis.hpa.state.il.us/hargis/PDFs/200181.pdf |date=1978-02-03 |accessdate=2008-07-07 |author=Robert Wagner |publisher=National Park Service |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090624112624/http://gis.hpa.state.il.us/hargis/PDFs/200181.pdf |archivedate=2009-06-24 }}</ref> It was also designated as a [[Chicago Landmark]] on October 2, 1991.<ref>{{cite news|last=Davis|first=Robert|title=City Makes Bridge a Landmark, Puts De Paul on State Street|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=October 3, 1991}}</ref> In 2009 the sidewalks and railings on the bridge were replaced, and the bridge was repainted; the design of the new ornamental railings was based on the original 1920 design for the bridge's railings, replacing more utilitarian ones that had been substituted at a later date.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kamin|first=Blair|title=Perfect timing for the Olympics inspection: Handsome new railings on the Michigan Avenue Bridge|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2009-04-05/news/0904030149_1_railings-michigan-avenue-bridge-east-side|accessdate=September 19, 2010|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=April 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Design and operation==\nMichigan Avenue Bridge is a double-leaf, double-deck, fixed [[counterweight]], trunnion bascule bridge.<ref name=\"HAER\" /> It was engineered by the Chicago Department of Public Works, Bureau of Engineering;<ref name=\"HAER\" /> [[Edward H. Bennett]] was the consulting architect and William A. Mulcahy the chief engineer of construction.<ref>{{cite web|last=McMahon|first=James D.|title=Plaque Commemorating Opening of Michigan Avenue Bridge|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/10481.html|work=The Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago|publisher=Chicago Historical Society|accessdate=September 25, 2010}}</ref> At the time of construction it was believed to be the first double-deck bridge ever built to have roadway on both levels; faster non-commercial traffic using the upper deck and slower commercial traffic that served the various industries and docks in the vicinity of the river using the lower deck.<ref name=\"Young 1920 p508\" />\n[[File:Michigan Ave Bridge 060415.jpg|thumb|left|The Michigan Avenue Bridge is raised twice weekly in the spring and fall to allow tall craft to winter near the river and have summer moorings on Lake Michigan harbors]]\n\nEach of the bridge's leaves is divided into two along the axis of the bridge such that it functions as two parallel bridges that can be operated independently of one another; at the time of construction bridges over the Chicago River were frequently struck by vessels, and this duplex arrangement allows for leaves damaged in such a collision to be opened for repair without needing to completely close the bridge to traffic.<ref>{{Harvnb|Young|1920|p=509}}</ref> The counterweights are below the level of the lower deck and when the bridge is opened they swing down into {{convert|40|ft|m|adj=mid|-deep}} reinforced concrete tailpits that descend {{convert|34.5|ft|m}} below the surface of the river.<ref name=\"Young and Mulcahey 1919\">{{Harvnb|Young|Mulcahey|1919|p=210}}</ref> Each of the two tailpits is supported on nine cylindrical foundation piers. One of these piers was sunk to [[bedrock]], {{convert|108|ft|m}} below the river surface, the other 17 piers are sunk to the [[hardpan]], which is {{convert|80|to|90|ft|m}} below the water level.<ref name=\"Young and Mulcahey 1919\" /> On the south side of the river one of the freight tunnels of the [[Chicago Tunnel Company]] had to be re-routed to make room for the tailpit.<ref name=\"Young and Mulcahey 1919\" /> The counterweights are composed partly of concrete and partly of a concrete composite with rivet punchings; each of the four counterweights weighs {{convert|1595|ST|MT}}.<ref>{{Harvnb|Young|1920|p=514}}</ref>\nThe Michigan Avenue Bridge is made of steel. The bridge can carry about 30,000 people daily.\n\nThe bridge abutments and the facing of the [[bridge tender's house|bridge tender houses]] are made of [[Indiana Limestone|Bedford stone]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Young|1921|p=364}}</ref> There are four bridge tender houses: the northwest and southeast bridgehouses house the controls for operating the bridge; the northeast and southwest bridgehouses are purely decorative.<ref name=\"Tribune20060607\">{{cite news|last=Mullen|first=William|title=House on the river bridges 8 decades - Hidden world will soon become museum - The fascinating and long-hidden world inside one of Chicago's stylish bridge-tender towers soon will be opened to visitors|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=June 7, 2006}}</ref> Two {{convert|108|hp}} motors open and close each of the {{convert|3750|ST|MT|adj=on}} bridge leaves.<ref>{{cite web|title=About the Bridge|url=http://bridgehousemuseum.org/about/the-bridge/|work=McCormick Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum website|publisher=McCormick Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum|accessdate=October 1, 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060617062619/http://bridgehousemuseum.org/about/the-bridge/|archivedate=June 17, 2006}}</ref> Originally the bridge was staffed 24 hours a day, and opened up to 3000 times a year to allow ships through, but since the 1970s bridge lifting has been scheduled in the spring and fall, when the bridge is raised twice weekly to allow sailboats to pass between [[Lake Michigan]] and inland boat yards where they are stored for the winter.<ref name=\"Tribune20060607\" />\n\n==Decoration==\n{{multiple image\n| footer   = Sculptures on the bridge tender houses. Left to right: ''The Discoverers'', ''The Pioneers'', ''Defense'', ''Regeneration''.\n\n| image1   = The Discoverers James Earle Fraser.jpg\n| alt1     = The Discoverers\n| width1 = 80\n\n| image2   = The Pioneers James Earle Fraser.jpg\n| alt2     = The Pioneers\n| width2 = 83\n\n| image3   = Defense Henry Hering.jpg\n| alt3     = Defense\n| width3 = 82\n\n| image4   = Regeneration Henry Hering.jpg\n| alt4     = Regeneration\n| width4 = 83\n}}\nIn 1928 sculptures depicting scenes from Chicago's history were added to the outward-facing walls of the four bridgehouses. The sculptures on the northern bridgehouses were commissioned by [[William Wrigley, Jr.]], and are by [[James Earle Fraser (sculptor)|James Earle Fraser]]: ''The Discoverers'' depicts [[Louis Joliet]], [[Jacques Marquette]], [[Ren\u00e9-Robert Cavelier, Sieur de La Salle]] and [[Henri de Tonti]];<ref>{{cite web|title=The Discoverers (sculpture)|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=X28666T8C7137.21008&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!7984~!1&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=The+Discoverers&index=.GW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1|work=Smithsonian Art Inventories Catalog|publisher=Smithsonian Institution|accessdate=October 9, 2010}}</ref> ''The Pioneers'' depicts [[John Kinzie]] leading a group through the wilderness.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Pioneers (sculpture)|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=1R8666523V41I.20726&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!8027~!0&ri=4&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=pioneer&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=james+earle+fraser&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=4|work=Smithsonian Art Inventories Catalog|publisher=Smithsonian Institution|accessdate=October 9, 2010}}</ref> The sculptures on the southern bridgehouses were commissioned by the [[Benjamin F. Ferguson]] Monument Fund, and are by [[Henry Hering]]: ''Defense'' depicts Ensign [[George Ronan]] in a scene from the 1812 [[Battle of Fort Dearborn]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Defense (sculpture)|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=128667N0QH558.21019&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!7983~!20&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Defense&index=.TW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1|work=Smithsonian Art Inventories Catalog|publisher=Smithsonian Institution|accessdate=October 9, 2010}}</ref> ''Regeneration'' depicts workers rebuilding Chicago after the [[Great Chicago Fire]] of 1871.<ref>{{cite web|title=Regeneration (sculpture)|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=ND8J670178268.21029&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!8028~!1&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Regeneration&index=.TW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1|work=Smithsonian Art Inventories Catalog|publisher=Smithsonian Institution|accessdate=October 9, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Stamper|first=John W.|title=Chicago's North Michigan Avenue: Planning and Development, 1900-1930|year=1991|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=0-226-77085-0|page=45}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge is also bedecked with 28 flagpoles, usually flying the flags of the United States, Illinois and Chicago. On special occasions other banners may be displayed.\n\n==McCormick Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum==\n[[File:Bridgehouse Museum 20101009.jpg|thumb|Entrance to the Bridgehouse Museum]]\nThe southwest bridgehouse has been converted into a museum, with its entrance off the [[Chicago Riverwalk]]. The McCormick Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum is a 5-floor, {{convert|1,613|sqft|m2|adj=on}} museum that opened on June 10, 2006; it is named for [[Robert R. McCormick]], formerly owner of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' and president of the Chicago Sanitary District.<ref name=\"Tribune20060607\" /> The Robert R. McCormick Foundation was the major donor that helped to provide the $950,000 cost of the formation of the museum.<ref name=\"Tribune20060607\" /> It is run by the Friends of the Chicago River,<ref>{{cite web|title=About the Museum|url=http://bridgehousemuseum.org/about/the-museum/|work=McCormick Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum website|publisher=McCormick Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum|accessdate=September 22, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100928020208/http://bridgehousemuseum.org/about/the-museum/|archivedate=September 28, 2010}}</ref> and includes exhibits on the history of the Chicago River and the bridge. Visitors are also allowed to access the bridge's gear room; during the spring and fall bridge lifting visitors can see the bridge gears in operation as the leaves are raised and lowered.<ref name=\"Tribune20060607\" /> Due to its small size and tight access stairway only 79 people are allowed inside the museum at any one time.<ref name=\"Tribune20060607\" />\n\nIn July 2019, the museum welcomed its 250,000th guest.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment-and-culture/2019/7/30/20746855/chicago-river-museum-gets-250k-visitors-mccormick-bridgehouse|title=Chicago River Museum Gets 250k Visitor|last=|first=|date=July 30, 2019|work=Associated Press|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> In October 2019, [[Chicago Tribune]] cultural arts writer Steve Johnson called the museum's gear room where the DuSable Bridge mechanics can be viewed working \"a little chamber of heaven for infrastructure nerds.\" <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/museums/ct-ent-chicago-river-museum-bridge-raising-view-ttd-1009-20191008-zckzgt2xjngpho6fd25j53sgz4-story.html|title=Hurried Chicagoans hate it when the river bridges open. The Chicago River Museum sells tickets.|last=Johnson|first=Steve|date=October 8, 2019|work=Chicago Tribune|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Historic Michigan Boulevard District]]\n*[[List of bridges documented by the Historic American Engineering Record in Illinois]]\n*[[Multilevel streets in Chicago]]\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Burnham|first=Daniel H.|authorlink=Daniel Burnham|last2=Bennett|first2=Edward H.|authorlink2=Edward H. Bennett|title=Plan of Chicago|year=1909|publisher=The Commercial Club of Chicago|url=https://archive.org/details/planofchicago00burnuoft|accessdate=September 19, 2010|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Young|first=Hugh E.|last2=Mulcahey|first2=William A.|title=Substructure of Michigan Avenue Bascule Bridge, Chicago|journal=Engineering News-Record|date=July 31, 1919|volume=83|issue=5|pages=210\u2013213|url=https://archive.org/details/engineeringnewsr83newy|accessdate=September 19, 2010|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Young|first=Hugh E.|title=Chicago Bascule Bridge\u2014Design and Operating Features|journal=Engineering News-Record|date=September 9, 1920|volume=85|issue=11|pages=508\u2013514|url=https://archive.org/details/engineeringnewsr85newy|accessdate=September 19, 2010|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Young|first=Hugh E.|title=The Michigan Boulevard Improvement|journal=Journal of the Western Society of Engineers|date=October 1921|volume=26|issue=10|pages=360\u2013368|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LZUPAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=September 19, 2010|ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.bridgehousemuseum.org McCormick Tribune Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum]\n\n{{Chicago Landmark transportation}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:1920 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Bascule bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1920]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Historic American Engineering Record in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Chicago Landmarks]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Road bridges on the National Register of Historic Places in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Steel bridges in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox bridge\n|bridge_name   = DuSable Bridge\n|image         = Michigan Ave Bridge 20100912.jpg\n|caption       = DuSable (Michigan Avenue) Bridge viewed from the west\n|official_name = \n|carries       = [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]]\n|crosses       = [[Chicago River]]\n|locale        = [[Chicago]]\n|maint         = \n|id            = 000016612026812\n|designer      = Bureau of Engineering, [[Chicago Department of Public Works]]\n|design        = Double-leaf, double-deck, fixed [[counterweight]], [[trunnion]] [[bascule bridge]]\n|material      =\n|spans         =\n|pierswater    = \n|length= {{convert|399|ft|m}}<ref>{{cite web|last=Holth|first=Nathan|title=Michigan Avenue Bridge|url=http://www.historicbridges.org/truss/michiganavenue/|work=HistoricBridges.org|accessdate=September 19, 2010}}</ref>\n|width= {{convert|91.75|ft|m}}<ref name=\"HAER\">{{cite web|last=Scott|first=Charles|last2=Alexander|first2=Frances|last3=Nicolay|first3=John|last4=Brucken|first4=Carolyn|title=Chicago River Bascule Bridge, Michigan Avenue|url=http://hdl.loc.gov/loc.pnp/hhh.il0630|work=Historic American Engineering Record|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=September 19, 2010}}</ref>\n|mainspan= {{convert|256|ft|m}} between trunnions<br />{{convert|220|ft|m}} between piers<ref name=\"Young 1920 p508\">{{Harvnb|Young|1920|p=508}}</ref>\n|height        = \n|load          = \n|clearance     = \n|below         = {{convert|16|ft|m}}\n|traffic       = 37900 (upper deck)<br />11700 (lower deck)<ref>2010 data from the National Bridge Inventory Database. {{cite web|title=National Bridge Inventory|url=http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/bridge/nbi/ascii.cfm?year=2011|publisher=U.S. Department of Transportation Federal Highway Administration|accessdate=2012-04-04}}</ref>\n|begin = April 15, 1918<ref name=\"Tribune19200514\">{{cite news|title=\"I Will\" Spirit Wins; Open Link Bridge Today|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=May 14, 1920|page=3}}</ref>\n|complete = 1920\n|open=May 14, 1920<ref name=\"Tribune19200514\" />\n|heritage = [[List of Chicago Landmarks|Chicago Landmark]]\n|collapsed     =\n|preceded      =\n|followed      =\n|closed        = \n|toll          = \n|map_cue       = \n|map_image     = \n|map_text      = \n|map_width     = \n|coordinates   = {{coord|41|53|19.9|N|87|37|27.7|W|region:US_type:landmark|display=it}}\n|extra         =\n}}\nThe '''DuSable Bridge''' (formerly, '''Michigan Avenue Bridge''') is a [[bascule bridge]] that carries [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]] across the main stem of the [[Chicago River]] in downtown [[Chicago]], Illinois, United States. The bridge was proposed in the early 20th century as part of a plan to link Chicago's south side and north side parks with a grand boulevard. Construction of the bridge started in 1918, it opened to traffic in 1920, and decorative work was completed in 1928. The bridge provides passage for vehicles and pedestrians on two levels. An example of a fixed [[trunnion]] bascule bridge (which is also known as a \"Chicago style bascule bridge\"), it may be raised to allow tall ships and boats to pass underneath. The bridge is included in the [[Michigan\u2013Wacker Historic District]] and has been designated as a [[Chicago Landmark]].\n\nThe location is significant in the early history of Chicago, connecting on the north near the 1780s homestead site of [[Jean Baptiste Point du Sable]] and on the south the early 19th century site of [[Fort Dearborn]]. Events from the city's past are commemorated with sculptures and plaques on the bridge, and exhibits in the McCormick Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum\u2014housed in one of the [[bridge tender's house|bridge tender houses]]\u2014detail the history of the Chicago River.\n\n==Location==\n{{multiple image\n| align=left\n| footer   = Aerial view of the bridge, looking south along [[Michigan Avenue (Chicago)|Michigan Avenue]], 1945 (left) and 2008 (right) \n| width    = 127\n\n| image1   = Michigan Ave looking south, Chicago, 6-20-1945.jpg\n| alt1     = 1945\n\n| image2   = Michigan Avenue Bridge 20080811.jpg\n| alt2     = 2010\n}}\n\nThe Michigan Avenue Bridge has a north\u2013south orientation, spanning the main stem of the Chicago River between the [[Near North Side, Chicago|Near North Side]] and [[Loop, Chicago|Loop]] [[Community areas of Chicago|community areas]] of Chicago.<ref>{{cite map |publisher=Google Inc |title=Google Maps |url=https://maps.google.com/maps?q=41.888861,-87.624361(Michigan+Avenue+Bridge)&ie=UTF8&ll=41.88886,-87.624357&spn=0.003582,0.005901&z=18 |accessdate=October 10, 2010}}</ref> Its northern portal lies at the foot of the [[Magnificent Mile]], between the [[Wrigley Building]] and [[Tribune Tower]]. Its southern portal is at the intersection of Michigan Avenue and [[Wacker Drive]], overlooked by the [[London Guarantee Building]] and [[333 North Michigan]]. The neighboring bridges are [[Columbus Drive Bridge (Chicago)|Columbus Drive Bridge]] to the east and [[Wabash Avenue Bridge]] to the west.\n\nThe bridge is situated in a historically significant area.<ref>{{cite book|last=Stamper|first=John W.|title=North Michigan Avenue: a building book from the Chicago Historical Society|year=2005|publisher=Pomegranate|isbn=0-7649-3382-5|page=8}}</ref> The northern end of the bridge covers part of the [[Jean Baptiste Point Du Sable Homesite]],{{#tag:ref|According to an 1892 description of the location of the house, it \"stood as nearly as may be at the foot of Pine Street <nowiki>[</nowiki>now Michigan Avenue<nowiki>]</nowiki>, partly upon the ground now occupied by Kirk's factory, and partly in what is now known as North Water Street, properly an extension of Kinzie Street.\" This location was confirmed by the recollections of John Noble, the last occupant of the house, who died in 1888.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Mason|first=Edward G.|title=Early Visitors to Chicago|journal=The New England Magazine|date=April 1892|volume=6|issue=2|pages=188\u2013206}}</ref>|group=n}} which is commemorated by a National Historic plaque in [[Pioneer Court]]. The southern half of the bridge passes over the site of [[Fort Dearborn]], which was constructed in 1803.{{#tag:ref|The south bank of the river where Fort Dearborn had stood was dredged in 1855, straightening the bend in the river and widening it at this point by about {{convert|150|ft|m}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Andreas|first=Alfred T.|title=History of Chicago, Volume 1|year=1884|publisher=A. T. Andreas|url=https://archive.org/details/historyofchicago01inandr|accessdate=September 19, 2010|page=[https://archive.org/details/historyofchicago01inandr/page/238 238]}}</ref>|group=n}} The Fort is commemorated by a large [[relief]] above the entrance of the London Guarantee Building, and brass markers positioned in the sidewalks on the south side of the bridge delineate the posited outline of the original [[blockhouse]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Old Fort Dearborn Site to be Outlined on Michigan Avenue|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=January 8, 1941}}</ref>\n\n==Name==\nThe historical significance of the location has been used as the basis for a number of proposals to rename the bridge. In 1921 the Chicago Historical Society suggested that the bridge should be named ''[[Jacques Marquette|Marquette]]\u2013[[Louis Joliet|Joliet]] Bridge'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Ave Bridge it is, and so it Stays|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=April 7, 1921}}</ref> and in 1939 it was proposed to rename the bridge as ''Fort Dearborn Bridge''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Urge Renaming of Bridge in Honor of Ft. Dearborn|newspaper=Chicago Daily Tribune|date=October 29, 1939}}</ref> These proposals were not adopted.\n\nIn October 2010, the bridge was renamed ''DuSable Bridge'' in honor of [[Jean Baptiste Point du Sable]], Chicago's first permanent resident.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cancino |first=Alejandra |title=Michigan Avenue bridge officially renamed DuSable Bridge |url=http://www.chicagobreakingnews.com/2010/10/michigan-avenue-bridge-officially-renamed-dusable-bridge.html |accessdate=October 16, 2010 |newspaper=Chicago Breaking News |date=October 15, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101019044214/http://www.chicagobreakingnews.com/2010/10/michigan-avenue-bridge-officially-renamed-dusable-bridge.html |archivedate=October 19, 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A fur trader of African descent who married into the [[Potawatomi]] tribe, he established a permanent homestead and trading post near the mouth of the Chicago River in the 1780s.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michigan Avenue Bridge becomes DuSable Bridge|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wls/story?section=news/local&id=7726430|accessdate=October 17, 2010|newspaper=WLS-TV|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101018072553/http://abclocal.go.com/wls/story?section=news%2Flocal&id=7726430|archive-date=October 18, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Plan of Chicago Plate CXII.jpg|thumb|right|Michigan Boulevard and bridge as proposed in Burnham & Bennett's [[1909 Plan of Chicago]] looking north from [[Grant Park (Chicago)|Grant Park]]]]\nA boulevard to link the parks on Chicago's north and south sides was proposed as early as 1891.<ref name=\"Tribune19200514\" /> An early plan called for a tunnel to link Michigan Avenue south of the river with Pine Street (now Michigan Avenue) north of the river.<ref>{{cite news|title=Great Boulevard Subway Project for Connecting North and South Divisions of the City|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=January 22, 1903|page=3}}</ref> In 1903 an editorial in the Chicago Tribune proposed a new bascule bridge across the river at Michigan Avenue.<ref>{{cite news|title=A Michigan Avenue Dream|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=May 31, 1903|page=16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Experts Praise Boulevard Plan|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=June 21, 1903|page=8}}</ref> Other plans suggested that the bridge should be a replica of the [[Pont Alexandre III]] that spans the Seine in Paris, or that, rather than constructing an entirely new bridge, the existing Rush Street bridge should be double-decked.<ref>{{cite news|title=Many Plans are Submitted for the Boulevard Link|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=June 11, 1904|page=4}}</ref>\n\nPlans for the boulevard and the construction of a Michigan Avenue Bridge were further elaborated upon in [[Daniel Burnham]]'s [[1909 Plan of Chicago]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Burnham|Bennett|1909|pp=101\u2013107}}</ref> In 1911 a plan was selected that included the widening of Michigan Avenue from Randolph Street to the river, replacing the Rush Street bridge with a new bridge at Michigan Avenue and the construction of a double-decked boulevard along Pine Street as far as Ohio Street.<ref>{{cite news|title=Wide Boulevard Scheme Chosen|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=July 11, 1911|page=3}}</ref> An ordinance to fund construction was passed in 1913, but was declared void by the [[Supreme Court of Illinois]].<ref>{{cite news|title=No Beginning on Boulevard Link for Three Years|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=May 6, 1915|page=13}}</ref> A second ordinance was passed in 1914, but legal battles continued until the end of 1916.<ref>{{cite news|title=Last Obstacle to Boulevard Link Removed|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=December 29, 1916|page=2}}</ref> Construction finally started on April 15, 1918, and the bridge was officially opened in a ceremony on May 14, 1920.<ref name=\"Tribune19200514\" />\n\nThe bridge is one of the contributing properties of the [[Michigan\u2013Wacker Historic District]], which was listed as on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] on November 15, 1978.<ref name=\"nrhpdoc\">{{Cite journal|title=National Register of Historic Places Inventory-Nomination: Michigan\u2013Wacker Historic District |url=http://gis.hpa.state.il.us/hargis/PDFs/200181.pdf |date=1978-02-03 |accessdate=2008-07-07 |author=Robert Wagner |publisher=National Park Service |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090624112624/http://gis.hpa.state.il.us/hargis/PDFs/200181.pdf |archivedate=2009-06-24 }}</ref> It was also designated as a [[Chicago Landmark]] on October 2, 1991.<ref>{{cite news|last=Davis|first=Robert|title=City Makes Bridge a Landmark, Puts De Paul on State Street|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=October 3, 1991}}</ref> In 2009 the sidewalks and railings on the bridge were replaced, and the bridge was repainted; the design of the new ornamental railings was based on the original 1920 design for the bridge's railings, replacing more utilitarian ones that had been substituted at a later date.<ref>{{cite news|last=Kamin|first=Blair|title=Perfect timing for the Olympics inspection: Handsome new railings on the Michigan Avenue Bridge|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2009-04-05/news/0904030149_1_railings-michigan-avenue-bridge-east-side|accessdate=September 19, 2010|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=April 5, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Design and operation==\nMichigan Avenue Bridge is a double-leaf, double-deck, fixed [[counterweight]], trunnion bascule bridge.<ref name=\"HAER\" /> It was engineered by the Chicago Department of Public Works, Bureau of Engineering;<ref name=\"HAER\" /> [[Edward H. Bennett]] was the consulting architect and William A. Mulcahy the chief engineer of construction.<ref>{{cite web|last=McMahon|first=James D.|title=Plaque Commemorating Opening of Michigan Avenue Bridge|url=http://www.encyclopedia.chicagohistory.org/pages/10481.html|work=The Electronic Encyclopedia of Chicago|publisher=Chicago Historical Society|accessdate=September 25, 2010}}</ref> At the time of construction it was believed to be the first double-deck bridge ever built to have roadway on both levels; faster non-commercial traffic using the upper deck and slower commercial traffic that served the various industries and docks in the vicinity of the river using the lower deck.<ref name=\"Young 1920 p508\" />\n[[File:Michigan Ave Bridge 060415.jpg|thumb|left|The Michigan Avenue Bridge is raised twice weekly in the spring and fall to allow tall craft to winter near the river and have summer moorings on Lake Michigan harbors]]\n\nEach of the bridge's leaves is divided into two along the axis of the bridge such that it functions as two parallel bridges that can be operated independently of one another; at the time of construction bridges over the Chicago River were frequently struck by vessels, and this duplex arrangement allows for leaves damaged in such a collision to be opened for repair without needing to completely close the bridge to traffic.<ref>{{Harvnb|Young|1920|p=509}}</ref> The counterweights are below the level of the lower deck and when the bridge is opened they swing down into {{convert|40|ft|m|adj=mid|-deep}} reinforced concrete tailpits that descend {{convert|34.5|ft|m}} below the surface of the river.<ref name=\"Young and Mulcahey 1919\">{{Harvnb|Young|Mulcahey|1919|p=210}}</ref> Each of the two tailpits is supported on nine cylindrical foundation piers. One of these piers was sunk to [[bedrock]], {{convert|108|ft|m}} below the river surface, the other 17 piers are sunk to the [[hardpan]], which is {{convert|80|to|90|ft|m}} below the water level.<ref name=\"Young and Mulcahey 1919\" /> On the south side of the river one of the freight tunnels of the [[Chicago Tunnel Company]] had to be re-routed to make room for the tailpit.<ref name=\"Young and Mulcahey 1919\" /> The counterweights are composed partly of concrete and partly of a concrete composite with rivet punchings; each of the four counterweights weighs {{convert|1595|ST|MT}}.<ref>{{Harvnb|Young|1920|p=514}}</ref>\nThe Michigan Avenue Bridge is made of steel. The bridge can carry about 30,000 people daily.\n\nThe bridge abutments and the facing of the [[bridge tender's house|bridge tender houses]] are made of [[Indiana Limestone|Bedford stone]].<ref>{{Harvnb|Young|1921|p=364}}</ref> There are four bridge tender houses: the northwest and southeast bridgehouses house the controls for operating the bridge; the northeast and southwest bridgehouses are purely decorative.<ref name=\"Tribune20060607\">{{cite news|last=Mullen|first=William|title=House on the river bridges 8 decades - Hidden world will soon become museum - The fascinating and long-hidden world inside one of Chicago's stylish bridge-tender towers soon will be opened to visitors|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=June 7, 2006}}</ref> Two {{convert|108|hp}} motors open and close each of the {{convert|3750|ST|MT|adj=on}} bridge leaves.<ref>{{cite web|title=About the Bridge|url=http://bridgehousemuseum.org/about/the-bridge/|work=McCormick Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum website|publisher=McCormick Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum|accessdate=October 1, 2006|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060617062619/http://bridgehousemuseum.org/about/the-bridge/|archivedate=June 17, 2006}}</ref> Originally the bridge was staffed 24 hours a day, and opened up to 3000 times a year to allow ships through, but since the 1970s bridge lifting has been scheduled in the spring and fall, when the bridge is raised twice weekly to allow sailboats to pass between [[Lake Michigan]] and inland boat yards where they are stored for the winter.<ref name=\"Tribune20060607\" />\n\n==Decoration==\n{{multiple image\n| footer   = Sculptures on the bridge tender houses. Left to right: ''The Discoverers'', ''The Pioneers'', ''Defense'', ''Regeneration''.\n\n| image1   = The Discoverers James Earle Fraser.jpg\n| alt1     = The Discoverers\n| width1 = 80\n\n| image2   = The Pioneers James Earle Fraser.jpg\n| alt2     = The Pioneers\n| width2 = 83\n\n| image3   = Defense Henry Hering.jpg\n| alt3     = Defense\n| width3 = 82\n\n| image4   = Regeneration Henry Hering.jpg\n| alt4     = Regeneration\n| width4 = 83\n}}\nIn 1928 sculptures depicting scenes from Chicago's history were added to the outward-facing walls of the four bridgehouses. The sculptures on the northern bridgehouses were commissioned by [[William Wrigley, Jr.]], and are by [[James Earle Fraser (sculptor)|James Earle Fraser]]: ''The Discoverers'' depicts [[Louis Joliet]], [[Jacques Marquette]], [[Ren\u00e9-Robert Cavelier, Sieur de La Salle]] and [[Henri de Tonti]];<ref>{{cite web|title=The Discoverers (sculpture)|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=X28666T8C7137.21008&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!7984~!1&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=The+Discoverers&index=.GW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1|work=Smithsonian Art Inventories Catalog|publisher=Smithsonian Institution|accessdate=October 9, 2010}}</ref> ''The Pioneers'' depicts [[John Kinzie]] leading a group through the wilderness.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Pioneers (sculpture)|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=1R8666523V41I.20726&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!8027~!0&ri=4&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=pioneer&index=.GW&uindex=&oper=&term=james+earle+fraser&index=.AW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=4|work=Smithsonian Art Inventories Catalog|publisher=Smithsonian Institution|accessdate=October 9, 2010}}</ref> The sculptures on the southern bridgehouses were commissioned by the [[Benjamin F. Ferguson]] Monument Fund, and are by [[Henry Hering]]: ''Defense'' depicts Ensign [[George Ronan]] in a scene from the 1812 [[Battle of Fort Dearborn]];<ref>{{cite web|title=Defense (sculpture)|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=128667N0QH558.21019&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!7983~!20&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Defense&index=.TW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1|work=Smithsonian Art Inventories Catalog|publisher=Smithsonian Institution|accessdate=October 9, 2010}}</ref> ''Regeneration'' depicts workers rebuilding Chicago after the [[Great Chicago Fire]] of 1871.<ref>{{cite web|title=Regeneration (sculpture)|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?session=ND8J670178268.21029&profile=ariall&source=~!siartinventories&view=subscriptionsummary&uri=full=3100001~!8028~!1&ri=1&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ipp=20&spp=20&staffonly=&term=Regeneration&index=.TW&uindex=&aspect=Keyword&menu=search&ri=1|work=Smithsonian Art Inventories Catalog|publisher=Smithsonian Institution|accessdate=October 9, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Stamper|first=John W.|title=Chicago's North Michigan Avenue: Planning and Development, 1900-1930|year=1991|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=0-226-77085-0|page=45}}</ref>\n\nThe bridge is also bedecked with 28 flagpoles, usually flying the flags of the United States, Illinois and Chicago. On special occasions other banners may be displayed.\n\n==McCormick Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum==\n[[File:Bridgehouse Museum 20101009.jpg|thumb|Entrance to the Bridgehouse Museum]]\nThe southwest bridgehouse has been converted into a museum, with its entrance off the [[Chicago Riverwalk]]. The McCormick Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum is a 5-floor, {{convert|1,613|sqft|m2|adj=on}} museum that opened on June 10, 2006; it is named for [[Robert R. McCormick]], formerly owner of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' and president of the Chicago Sanitary District.<ref name=\"Tribune20060607\" /> The Robert R. McCormick Foundation was the major donor that helped to provide the $950,000 cost of the formation of the museum.<ref name=\"Tribune20060607\" /> It is run by the Friends of the Chicago River,<ref>{{cite web|title=About the Museum|url=http://bridgehousemuseum.org/about/the-museum/|work=McCormick Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum website|publisher=McCormick Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum|accessdate=September 22, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100928020208/http://bridgehousemuseum.org/about/the-museum/|archivedate=September 28, 2010}}</ref> and includes exhibits on the history of the Chicago River and the bridge. Visitors are also allowed to access the bridge's gear room; during the spring and fall bridge lifting visitors can see the bridge gears in operation as the leaves are raised and lowered.<ref name=\"Tribune20060607\" /> Due to its small size and tight access stairway only 79 people are allowed inside the museum at any one time.<ref name=\"Tribune20060607\" />\n\nIn July of 2019, the museum welcomed its 250,000th guest.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment-and-culture/2019/7/30/20746855/chicago-river-museum-gets-250k-visitors-mccormick-bridgehouse|title=Chicago River Museum Gets 250k Visitor|last=|first=|date=July 30, 2019|work=Associated Press|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref> In October of 2019, [[Chicago Tribune]] cultural arts writer Steve Johnson called the museum's gear room where the DuSable Bridge mechanics can be viewed working \"a little chamber of heaven for infrastructure nerds.\" <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/museums/ct-ent-chicago-river-museum-bridge-raising-view-ttd-1009-20191008-zckzgt2xjngpho6fd25j53sgz4-story.html|title=Hurried Chicagoans hate it when the river bridges open. The Chicago River Museum sells tickets.|last=Johnson|first=Steve|date=October 8, 2019|work=Chicago Tribune|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Historic Michigan Boulevard District]]\n*[[List of bridges documented by the Historic American Engineering Record in Illinois]]\n*[[Multilevel streets in Chicago]]\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|group=n}}\n\n===References===\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last=Burnham|first=Daniel H.|authorlink=Daniel Burnham|last2=Bennett|first2=Edward H.|authorlink2=Edward H. Bennett|title=Plan of Chicago|year=1909|publisher=The Commercial Club of Chicago|url=https://archive.org/details/planofchicago00burnuoft|accessdate=September 19, 2010|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Young|first=Hugh E.|last2=Mulcahey|first2=William A.|title=Substructure of Michigan Avenue Bascule Bridge, Chicago|journal=Engineering News-Record|date=July 31, 1919|volume=83|issue=5|pages=210\u2013213|url=https://archive.org/details/engineeringnewsr83newy|accessdate=September 19, 2010|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Young|first=Hugh E.|title=Chicago Bascule Bridge\u2014Design and Operating Features|journal=Engineering News-Record|date=September 9, 1920|volume=85|issue=11|pages=508\u2013514|url=https://archive.org/details/engineeringnewsr85newy|accessdate=September 19, 2010|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Young|first=Hugh E.|title=The Michigan Boulevard Improvement|journal=Journal of the Western Society of Engineers|date=October 1921|volume=26|issue=10|pages=360\u2013368|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LZUPAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=September 19, 2010|ref=harv}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.bridgehousemuseum.org McCormick Tribune Bridgehouse & Chicago River Museum]\n\n{{Chicago Landmark transportation}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:1920 establishments in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Bascule bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1920]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Historic American Engineering Record in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Landmarks in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures on the National Register of Historic Places in Chicago]]\n[[Category:Road bridges on the National Register of Historic Places in Illinois]]\n[[Category:Steel bridges in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DuSable_Bridge"}
{"title_page": "1,2-Cyclohexanediamine", "text_new": "{{Chembox\n| IUPACName = Cyclohexane-1,2-diamine\n|Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers\n| PubChem = 4610\n| CASNo = 694-83-7\n| EC_number = 211-776-7\n| UNNumber = 2735\n| ChEMBL = 1356279\n| ChEBI = 93778\n| ChemSpiderID = 4449\n| StdInChI=1S/C6H14N2/c7-5-3-1-2-4-6(5)8/h5-6H,1-4,7-8H2\n| StdInChIKey = SSJXIUAHEKJCMH-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| SMILES = C1CCC(C(C1)N)N\n }}\n|Section2 = {{Chembox Properties\n| C=6|H=14|N=2\n }}\n|Section7 = {{Chembox Hazards\n| GHSPictograms = {{GHS05}}{{GHS07}}\n| GHSSignalWord = Danger\n| HPhrases = {{H-phrases|302|312|314|317|318|332|335}}\n| PPhrases = {{P-phrases|260|261|264|270|271|272|280|301+312|301+330+331|302+352|303+361+353|304+312|304+340|305+351+338|310|312|321|322|330|333+313|363|403+233|405|501}}\n }}\n}}\n\n'''1,2-Cyclohexanediamine''' is an organic compound with the formula (CH<sub>2</sub>)<sub>4</sub>(CHNH<sub>2</sub>)<sub>2</sub>. Described by the registry number [[CAS Registry number]] (RN) 694-83-7 is a mixture of the two [[diastereoisomer]]s, [[trans-1,2-Diaminocyclohexane|''trans''-1,2-diaminocyclohexane]] (RN 1121-22-8) and ''cis''-1,2-diaminocyclohexane (RN 1436-59-5).  The mixture is a colorless, corrosive liquid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/4610|title=1,2-Cyclohexanediamine|last=PubChem|website=pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>.  It is often called DCH-99 and also DACH.\n\n== Manufacture ==\n\nThe product is available commercially as Dytek DCH-99. It may be manufactured by the [[hydrogenation]] of [[o-phenylenediamine]]<ref>{{Citation|last=Kouklovsky|first=Cyrille|title=(1S,2S)-1,2-Diaminocyclohexane|date=2014|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/047084289X.rn00145.pub3|work=Encyclopedia of Reagents for Organic Synthesis|pages=1\u201323|publisher=American Cancer Society|language=en|doi=10.1002/047084289x.rn00145.pub3|isbn=978-0-470-84289-8|access-date=2020-04-13|last2=Langlois|first2=Yves|last3=Aguilar|first3=Enrique|last4=Fern\u00e1ndez\u2010Garc\u00eda|first4=Jes\u00fas M.|last5=Sikervar|first5=Vikas}}</ref>.\n\n== Uses ==\nThe product is used in the production of epoxy curing agents for use in [[Coatings]], [[Adhesives]], [[Sealants]] and [[Elastomers]] - CASE<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ulprospector.com/en/la/Coatings/Detail/25290/557016/Dytek-DCH-99|title=Dytek\u00ae DCH-99 by INVISTA - Paint & Coatings|website=www.ulprospector.com|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>. It may also be reacted with diethyl maleate utilizing the [[Michael reaction]] to produce a [[polyaspartic]] compound<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dytek.invista.com/products/dytek-dch-99/|title=Dytek\u00ae DCH-99 {{!}} 1,2-Diaminocyclohexane|website=Dytek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> of CAS number 481040-92-0. It may also be used in lubricants<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patents.justia.com/patent/9273266|title=US Patent for Non-aromatic based antioxidants for lubricants Patent (Patent # 9,273,266 issued March 1, 2016) - Justia Patents Search|website=patents.justia.com|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>. The poroduct is also advertised as being useful as a [[chelating agent]] in a variety of applications including oil production<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dytek.invista.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Dytek%E2%94%AC%C2%AB-DCH-99-12-Diaminocyclohexane-Technical-Data-Sheet.pdf|title=Technical Data Sheet Dytek  DCH 99|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[trans-1,2-Diaminocyclohexane]]\n* [[Hexamethylenediamine]]\n* [[Isophorone diamine]]\n* [[1,3-BAC]]\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using<ref></ref> tags, these references will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://datasheets.globalspec.com/ds/1567/INVISTA/5D0F80C5-8C40-4033-BF35-F39A5F27E875  Engineering 360 website]\n* [https://dytek.invista.com/products/dytek-dch-99/ Invista website]\n* [https://www.sigmaaldrich.com/MSDS/MSDS/DisplayMSDSPage.do?country=US&language=en&productNumber=132551&brand=ALDRICH&PageToGoToURL=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.sigmaaldrich.com%2Fcatalog%2Fproduct%2Faldrich%2F132551%3Flang%3Den SDS Sigma Aldrich]\n* [https://www.gracoroberts.com/home/download/invista-dytek-dch-99-amine-epoxy-coating-sds/ Safety Data Sheet]\n<!--- Categories --->\n\n[[Category:Diamines]]\n", "text_old": "{{Chembox\n| IUPACName = cyclohexane-1,2-diamine\n|Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers\n| PubChem = 4610\n| CASNo = 694-83-7\n| EC_number = 211-776-7\n| UNNumber = 2735\n| ChEMBL = 1356279\n| ChEBI = 93778\n| ChemSpiderID = 4449\n| StdInChI=1S/C6H14N2/c7-5-3-1-2-4-6(5)8/h5-6H,1-4,7-8H2\n| StdInChIKey = SSJXIUAHEKJCMH-UHFFFAOYSA-N\n| SMILES = C1CCC(C(C1)N)N\n }}\n|Section2 = {{Chembox Properties\n| C=6|H=14|N=2\n }}\n|Section7 = {{Chembox Hazards\n| GHSPictograms = {{GHS05}}{{GHS07}}\n| GHSSignalWord = Danger\n| HPhrases = {{H-phrases|302|312|314|317|318|332|335}}\n| PPhrases = {{P-phrases|260|261|264|270|271|272|280|301+312|301+330+331|302+352|303+361+353|304+312|304+340|305+351+338|310|312|321|322|330|333+313|363|403+233|405|501}}\n }}\n}}\n\n'''1,2-Cyclohexanediamine''' is an organic compound with the formula (CH2)4(CHNH2)2. Described by the registry number [[CAS Registry number]] (RN) 694-83-7 is a mixture of the two [[diastereoisomer]]s, [[trans-1,2-Diaminocyclohexane|''trans''-1,2-diaminocyclohexane]] (RN 1121-22-8) and ''cis''-1,2-diaminocyclohexane (RN 1436-59-5).  The mixture is a colorless, corrosive liquid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/4610|title=1,2-Cyclohexanediamine|last=PubChem|website=pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>.  It is often called DCH-99 and also DACH.\n\n== Manufacture ==\n\nThe product is available commercially as Dytek DCH-99. It may be manufactured by the [[hydrogenation]] of [[o-phenylenediamine]]<ref>{{Citation|last=Kouklovsky|first=Cyrille|title=(1S,2S)-1,2-Diaminocyclohexane|date=2014|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/047084289X.rn00145.pub3|work=Encyclopedia of Reagents for Organic Synthesis|pages=1\u201323|publisher=American Cancer Society|language=en|doi=10.1002/047084289x.rn00145.pub3|isbn=978-0-470-84289-8|access-date=2020-04-13|last2=Langlois|first2=Yves|last3=Aguilar|first3=Enrique|last4=Fern\u00e1ndez\u2010Garc\u00eda|first4=Jes\u00fas M.|last5=Sikervar|first5=Vikas}}</ref>.\n\n== Uses ==\nThe product is used in the production of epoxy curing agents for use in [[Coatings]], [[Adhesives]], [[Sealants]] and [[Elastomers]] - CASE<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ulprospector.com/en/la/Coatings/Detail/25290/557016/Dytek-DCH-99|title=Dytek\u00ae DCH-99 by INVISTA - Paint & Coatings|website=www.ulprospector.com|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>. It may also be reacted with diethyl maleate utilizing the [[Michael reaction]] to produce a [[polyaspartic]] compound<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dytek.invista.com/products/dytek-dch-99/|title=Dytek\u00ae DCH-99 {{!}} 1,2-Diaminocyclohexane|website=Dytek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref> of CAS number 481040-92-0. It may also be used in lubricants<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://patents.justia.com/patent/9273266|title=US Patent for Non-aromatic based antioxidants for lubricants Patent (Patent # 9,273,266 issued March 1, 2016) - Justia Patents Search|website=patents.justia.com|access-date=2020-04-13}}</ref>. The poroduct is also advertised as being useful as a [[chelating agent]] in a variety of applications including oil production<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dytek.invista.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Dytek%E2%94%AC%C2%AB-DCH-99-12-Diaminocyclohexane-Technical-Data-Sheet.pdf|title=Technical Data Sheet Dytek  DCH 99|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[trans-1,2-Diaminocyclohexane]]\n* [[Hexamethylenediamine]]\n* [[Isophorone diamine]]\n* [[1,3-BAC]]\n\n== References ==\n<!--- See http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Footnotes on how to create references using<ref></ref> tags, these references will then appear here automatically -->\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://datasheets.globalspec.com/ds/1567/INVISTA/5D0F80C5-8C40-4033-BF35-F39A5F27E875  Engineering 360 website]\n* [https://dytek.invista.com/products/dytek-dch-99/ Invista website]\n* [https://www.sigmaaldrich.com/MSDS/MSDS/DisplayMSDSPage.do?country=US&language=en&productNumber=132551&brand=ALDRICH&PageToGoToURL=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.sigmaaldrich.com%2Fcatalog%2Fproduct%2Faldrich%2F132551%3Flang%3Den SDS Sigma Aldrich]\n* [https://www.gracoroberts.com/home/download/invista-dytek-dch-99-amine-epoxy-coating-sds/ Safety Data Sheet]\n<!--- Categories --->\n\n[[Category:Diamines]]\n", "name_user": "Gyimhu", "label": "safe", "comment": "< sub >s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1,2-Cyclohexanediamine"}
